post_text:
Hello Family and Friends of the Autrey House Museum!

It's almost time for the annual Autrey Family and Friends Reunion. It will be held Sept. 24th at the Autrey House in Dubach, La. You can learn all about it at the "Absalom and Elizabeth Norris Autrey Annual Reunion" facebook event page. There are also some updates about the Autrey House Museum posted on the "Autrey House Museum" facebook page.

You'll read there about a fundraising project sponsored by Jeff and Yvonne Autrey, to benefit the Autrey House Museum. They have arranged for Tommy's tees in Ruston to make tee shirts with the Autrey House photo. I'm enclosing the link for any who would like to purchase the shirts.

Hope to see you all at the reunion!

http://www.tommystees.com/store/fundraising-shop/autrey-house

See you in September. Vicki Colvin

post_text: According to Jeff Autrey, the Absalom Autrey descendant reunion will be Sept. 24 2016 at the old Autrey House in Dubach LA. We schedule it the same weekend they have the Chicken Festival every year. We'll have a potluck lunch around noon, with some good old fashion Dutch Oven cooking. Bring your instruments if you play one for some old bluegrass music afterwards. Hope to see you there. Jeff is a sixth generation descendant of Absalom, through William Norris.

post_text: The Family Room of the Autrey House, with the wood stove to the left and the fireplace in the center. Generations of Autrey's spent time in front of this fireplace, enjoying the solace and warmth it brought. A portrait of Columbia Anne Autrey Scarborough hangs over the fireplace. She was the daughter of Robert Martin Autrey and Elizabeth Jane Kemp.

post_text:
Dear Family and Friends of the Autrey House Museum:

We are having an open house at the Autrey House Museum in Dubach, La., Saturday, Oct 24th from 1 to 4 PM. This event will include "spooky" stories for children from 1:30 to 2:00 PM and music on the porch from 2:00 to 4:00 PM. provided by a local jam group. Come join us for the fun! DON'T FORGET YOUR LAWN CHAIRS. Old family photos, Autrey House prints, and the Absalom Autrey genealogy book will be available for purchase. I will be happy to talk about the house and family history to those who may have questions. Hope to see you there! Vicki Colvin, President, Autrey House Museum Advisory Board.

From Ruston take 167 N to Dubach, West on Hwy 151 about a mile

post_text:
Dear Friends and family of the Autrey House,

Saturday, June 20th, we're having another open house at the Autrey House in Dubach, La., from 1 till 4 pm. We have an extra treat with two story tellers, telling stories about olden days in the Dubach area. Randy Rogers will start at 1:00 with stories from his books about Dubach. He will be followed by Bill Pendergrass, another local personality known for his interesting stories. Another dog trot house in Dubach, the Colvin house, will also be open for viewing. We hope you can come join us. Be sure to visit the Autrey House Museum on face book for updates on our progress on restoration. Vicki Colvin, President - Autrey House Museum Advisory Committee.

post_text:
Posted by Gary E. Gray - Your Autrey House Committee members hard at work on April 17, 2015 at the Lincoln Parish Museum. We discussed fund raising ideas to raise money for the needed repairs to the Historic Autrey House, along with other business.

We also discussed some community oriented events at the house to raise public awareness of this beautiful historic landmark. One idea that everyone seemed to like was possibly organizing a community festival type event with banjo music, food, and just a general good time for families and children.

Funds are low and we need to re-energize fund raising efforts. Start today by sending whatever you can, $10, $20, $100, any amount is welcome and needed. Send tax deductible donations to:

Autrey House Museum
c/o Lincoln Parish Museum
609 N Vienna St.
Ruston, La. 71270

MAKE CHECKS PAYABLE TO AUTREY HOUSE MUSEUM

Sign up for our email newsletter list! http://tiny.cc/autreyhouse

post_text:
William Henry Autry, great grand son of Cornelius and Elizabeth Paige Culbreth Autrey, was born in 1808 in Sampson County, North Carolina where he lived his entire life. He married Jane Riley and three of their children married three children of Daniel Mc Culbreth and Jennet Maxwell.

Son of Newsom Autry (b. 1780 NC) and Nancy Pharis (b. 1781 NC)
William Page Autry (b. 1745, Edgecombe Cty, NC) married Rachel U. Autry (b. 1749, NC)
Cornelius Autry (b. 1709) married Paige (b. 1710)
William Pharris (b. 1760 Jackson Cty, TN) married Katherine Johnson (b. abt. 1764)
text:
William Henry Autry, great grand son of Cornelius and Elizabeth Paige Culbreth Autrey, was born in 1808 in Sampson County, North Carolina where he lived his entire life. He married Jane Riley and three of their children married three children of Daniel Mc Culbreth and Jennet Maxwell.

Son of Newsom Autry (b. 1780 NC) and Nancy Pharis (b. 1781 NC)
William Page Autry (b. 1745, Edgecombe Cty, NC) married Rachel U. Autry (b. 1749, NC)
Cornelius Autry (b. 1709) married Paige (b. 1710)
William Pharris (b. 1760 Jackson Cty, TN) married Katherine Johnson (b. abt. 1764)

post_text: Post by Gary E. Gray, 3X great grandson of Absalom and Elizabeth Autrey. We toured the Alamo today, our son Connor has a school project in which he has to write about three historical sites that are significant to Texas independence. He chose the Alamo as one of those sites. One of the things I had discovered about a year ago while doing genealogy on my Autrey line is that Micajah Autry is a possible distant relation. I am still researching this line but I believe Micajah is the grandson of my 4X great grandfather, Cornelius Autry from Sampson, North Carolina. We saw Micajah's name inscribed at the Alamo and there is even an original letter he wrote to his wife that is displayed at the Alamo. Very interesting history at the Alamo and very interesting to see a possible distant relation who fought and died there.

post_text:
Upload your Autrey family photos here and share with all the other Autrey descendants out there! The attached picture is one my Aunt Barbara Tubbs Talbot found and I had restored. The picture shows the family of my great great grandfather Charlie Autrey and his second wife, Willie Joanna Michael Autrey.

Picture circa 1894. From left to right first row: Otha Joanna Autrey, Charles Henry Autrey, 2nd wife - Willie Joanna Michael Autrey, James Robert Autrey, Lela Michael Autrey, Emma Lucinda Autrey. Standing: Mary Pearl Autrey, Laura Alice Autrey, Elizabeth "Betty" Bush Autrey. Picture courtesy of Barbara Tubbs Talbot. Sadly, Otha, James, Lela and Emma would not survive long after this picture was taken.
